<article>
  <h1>DITA Reuse and Variants</h1>

  <section>
    <h2>Overview</h2>
    <p>Content reuse is a key benefit of DITA. You can reuse
    content at multiple levels using different mechanisms.</p>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>Conref</h2>
    <p>The conref mechanism lets you pull content from one
    topic into another. It works like a symlink for content.</p>
    <p>Example:</p>
    <pre>&lt;p conref="shared/warnings.dita#warnings/safety-warning"/&gt;</pre>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>Keyref</h2>
    <p>Keys provide indirect references. Define a key in
    your map, then reference it in topics.</p>
    <p>For example, define a key in your map:</p>
    <pre>&lt;keydef keys="product-name"&gt;
  &lt;topicmeta&gt;&lt;keywords&gt;&lt;keyword&gt;WidgetPro&lt;/keyword&gt;&lt;/keywords&gt;&lt;/topicmeta&gt;
&lt;/keydef&gt;</pre>
    <p>Then use it in any topic:</p>
    <pre>&lt;ph keyref="product-name"/&gt;</pre>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>DITAVAL Filtering</h2>
    <p>Use DITAVAL files to include or exclude content based
    on audience, platform, or product attributes.</p>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>Best Practices</h2>
    <ul>
      <li>Always use keys for product names</li>
      <li>Prefer keyref over conref when possible</li>
      <li>Test all variants before publishing</li>
    </ul>
  </section>
</article>
